1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,640
 So now we're going to do more than just console.log

2
00:00:02,640 --> 00:00:04,600
 so we can see what's going on in JavaScript,

3
00:00:04,600 --> 00:00:08,500
 but we're actually going to do modifying the document object model in JavaScript.

4
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:14,400
 So recall on the o1noscript.htm that I just used the debugger

5
00:00:14,400 --> 00:00:16,980
 to modify the document object model, right?

6
00:00:16,980 --> 00:00:19,440
 We modify the document object model,

7
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:21,580
 and if it's visible through the window,

8
00:00:21,580 --> 00:00:24,440
 then what we changed is instantly changed.

9
00:00:24,440 --> 00:00:26,500
 So literally, we're running JavaScript on one end,

10
00:00:26,500 --> 00:00:29,480
 and the UI just changes. It's like it instantaneously.

11
00:00:29,600 --> 00:00:34,200
 Although if you make mistakes and you run code that runs too long,

12
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:35,540
 those changes will be delayed

13
00:00:35,540 --> 00:00:37,940
 because we have to finish the JavaScript code

14
00:00:37,940 --> 00:00:40,180
 and let the browser do the redisplay.

15
00:00:40,180 --> 00:00:42,240
 But we can change these by hand,

16
00:00:42,240 --> 00:00:44,680
 but let's just do this instead with a trigger.

17
00:00:44,680 --> 00:00:47,940
 And to trigger it, we have to be able to grab bits of the DOM

18
00:00:47,940 --> 00:00:49,940
 or query the document object model.

19
00:00:49,940 --> 00:00:53,940
 Let's recall 03event.htm, and all we're showing here

20
00:00:53,940 --> 00:00:57,000
 is that we can define a function in JavaScript,

21
00:00:57,140 --> 00:01:00,380
 then we can have an onClick method that calls my function

22
00:01:00,380 --> 00:01:01,940
 after the click happens.

23
00:01:01,940 --> 00:01:04,340
 Again, remember that those quotes are important.

24
00:01:04,340 --> 00:01:07,580
 onClick attribute is a string,

25
00:01:07,580 --> 00:01:10,340
 which is only parsed at the moment that you click it,

26
00:01:10,340 --> 00:01:13,880
 and then func is called in that moment.

27
00:01:13,880 --> 00:01:15,880
 So let's do something a little more interesting

28
00:01:15,880 --> 00:01:17,640
 in that onClick method.

29
00:01:17,640 --> 00:01:22,040
 So the top part is still an ID tag, an h1,

30
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:23,940
 except now we put id equals fun,

31
00:01:23,940 --> 00:01:26,240
 and you can choose anything you want for the ID.

32
00:01:26,380 --> 00:01:28,140
 It's got to be unique across the whole document.

33
00:01:28,140 --> 00:01:29,480
 Remember CSS.

34
00:01:29,480 --> 00:01:32,780
 And then it has a bunch of attributes and methods.

35
00:01:32,780 --> 00:01:34,340
 Elements have attributes and methods,

36
00:01:34,340 --> 00:01:36,480
 and one of them is innerHTML.

37
00:01:36,480 --> 00:01:42,500
 And I simply assign the innerHTML to a cool header.

38
00:01:42,500 --> 00:01:45,240
 And that's how you basically see that change.

39
00:01:45,240 --> 00:01:46,680
 We're changing the element.

40
00:01:46,680 --> 00:01:49,180
 Now, an important part of this is the function ends,

41
00:01:49,180 --> 00:01:51,480
 so it goes back into the browser

42
00:01:51,480 --> 00:01:53,800
 and the browser sees the change to the document object model

43
00:01:53,800 --> 00:01:54,940
 and then displays it.

44
00:01:55,080 --> 00:01:58,500
 If we did something crazy in the last line of my func

45
00:01:58,500 --> 00:02:03,300
 that did not give the thread back to the browser,

46
00:02:03,300 --> 00:02:06,540
 it might get messed up, but we're going to just return.

47
00:02:06,540 --> 00:02:08,540
 We're going to make our change to document object model.

48
00:02:08,540 --> 00:02:12,480
 This code here, console.log let lm equals console.log lm

49
00:02:12,480 --> 00:02:14,500
 innerHTML, that's really quick.

50
00:02:14,500 --> 00:02:16,840
 Just in a blink of an eye, that code runs,

51
00:02:16,840 --> 00:02:18,800
 meaning there's nothing slow in it.

52
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:21,400
 Everything happens fast. There's nothing to wait for.

53
00:02:21,400 --> 00:02:22,740
 So everything happens fast.

54
00:02:22,880 --> 00:02:25,980
 We get the browser back to redisplay things.

55
00:02:25,980 --> 00:02:28,400
 And so you can see when you click on it,

56
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:30,240
 you can see that it says, "I was clicked."

57
00:02:30,240 --> 00:02:32,240
 It goes and looks the element up and it says,

58
00:02:32,240 --> 00:02:34,700
 "Oh, I just found an H1 tag."

59
00:02:34,700 --> 00:02:37,900
 And then I set its innerHTML to be a cool header.

60
00:02:37,900 --> 00:02:40,540
 I could have appended something

61
00:02:40,540 --> 00:02:43,340
 because I could have read innerHTML if I felt like it.

62
00:02:43,340 --> 00:02:46,440
 But then as soon as that function finishes,

63
00:02:46,440 --> 00:02:50,680
 then the browser takes over and then redisplays the updated DOM.

64
00:02:50,800 --> 00:02:54,600
 And again, everything that we did happens so rapidly

65
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:56,980
 that you don't even notice it.

66
00:02:56,980 --> 00:02:59,380
 So now let's add some stuff to the DOM.

67
00:02:59,380 --> 00:03:04,380
 We can completely build a tag and we can add it to the DOM.

68
00:03:04,380 --> 00:03:06,240
 Everything we've done so far is find a tag,

69
00:03:06,240 --> 00:03:08,180
 mess with it and then put it back.

70
00:03:08,180 --> 00:03:09,880
 So let's add something to the DOM.

71
00:03:09,880 --> 00:03:15,100
 This is a little bit more intricate, but we're going...

72
00:03:15,100 --> 00:03:19,500
 And this is a source code 09-append.htm

73
00:03:19,640 --> 00:03:21,280
 if you want to go play with it.

74
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:24,640
 So we're going to have a little button, an anchor tag,

75
00:03:24,640 --> 00:03:26,880
 and we're going to have an add, call the add function.

76
00:03:26,880 --> 00:03:29,700
 And then what you'll notice is we have a UL tag

77
00:03:29,700 --> 00:03:33,200
 and I've got an ID of Zap on the UL tag.

78
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:37,580
 And then the first item is li, list item tag and then /ul.

79
00:03:37,580 --> 00:03:40,740
 And then in the JavaScript,

80
00:03:40,740 --> 00:03:43,440
 I create a global variable called counter equals one.

81
00:03:43,440 --> 00:03:46,300
 And then I create a function called add.

82
00:03:46,440 --> 00:03:49,840
 And in that function, I go create a new create element.

83
00:03:49,840 --> 00:03:53,180
 Document.createElement says make me a new element.

84
00:03:53,180 --> 00:03:57,480
 I want an element of a tag, an li tag.

85
00:03:57,480 --> 00:04:01,040
 And then I can set things. I can set its class name.

86
00:04:01,040 --> 00:04:03,340
 I can set its inner HTML.

87
00:04:03,340 --> 00:04:05,440
 I'm concatenating the word the counter is

88
00:04:05,440 --> 00:04:07,180
 and then I'm concatenating the number.

89
00:04:07,180 --> 00:04:13,740
 And then I'm going to go document get element ID Zap.

90
00:04:13,880 --> 00:04:17,180
 Now, that is the UL tag, a pen child.

91
00:04:17,180 --> 00:04:20,040
 So the li tag is a child of the UL tag.

92
00:04:20,040 --> 00:04:24,340
 And by saying a pen child, I say I want to make a new child of this UL tag.

93
00:04:24,340 --> 00:04:27,700
 And so that's when you click it and then counter goes up by one.

94
00:04:27,700 --> 00:04:29,040
 And it's a global variable.

95
00:04:29,040 --> 00:04:32,100
 So kind of every time we call add, that counter goes up.

96
00:04:32,100 --> 00:04:35,840
 So first item, you click it, it says the counter is one.

97
00:04:35,840 --> 00:04:37,480
 You click it again, it adds counters too.

98
00:04:37,480 --> 00:04:38,640
 Click it again, it adds counters too.

99
00:04:38,640 --> 00:04:40,440
 You can do this as many times you like.

100
00:04:40,580 --> 00:04:45,580
 But the idea of making a new tag that's not connected to the document,

101
00:04:45,580 --> 00:04:48,580
 we make an li tag, we set some stuff in it,

102
00:04:48,580 --> 00:04:51,680
 and then we plug it into the document with a pen child.

103
00:04:51,680 --> 00:04:55,080
 If you look at the, it starts out with first item.

104
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:58,440
 And you'll notice, of course, that the more button

105
00:04:58,440 --> 00:05:00,040
 has an event associated with it.

106
00:05:00,040 --> 00:05:02,180
 We created that event with the onclick.

107
00:05:02,180 --> 00:05:06,280
 And then after we click it a couple times, boom, boom, boom,

108
00:05:06,280 --> 00:05:08,200
 it just adds those things.

109
00:05:08,340 --> 00:05:11,000
 So we can manipulate many things in the document object model

110
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,600
 from JavaScript, including changing the CSS,

111
00:05:13,600 --> 00:05:16,700
 which means we can alter the look of things.

112
00:05:16,700 --> 00:05:22,280
 And so in this, we've got a header tag with an idea of fun.

113
00:05:22,280 --> 00:05:25,700
 Again, the idea is a way for us to grab it in JavaScript, okay?

114
00:05:25,700 --> 00:05:29,100
 And then we're going to have a button with an idea of poof

115
00:05:29,100 --> 00:05:32,980
 and a button, an idea of show that has the text hide and show.

116
00:05:32,980 --> 00:05:37,240
 And we're going to do this using add event listener.

117
00:05:37,380 --> 00:05:39,740
 There are shorter, we could have used the onclick,

118
00:05:39,740 --> 00:05:41,800
 but I just want to kind of get used to the notion

119
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:45,240
 that one of the things you do toward the end of your document

120
00:05:45,240 --> 00:05:47,440
 is you add all the event listeners.

121
00:05:47,440 --> 00:05:49,300
 So you have all the HTML that gets displayed,

122
00:05:49,300 --> 00:05:51,980
 and then after that, you add event listeners.

123
00:05:51,980 --> 00:05:56,340
 And so in that script, we do document, get element, ID, show,

124
00:05:56,340 --> 00:05:58,700
 and then we're going to add an event listener.

125
00:05:58,700 --> 00:06:00,540
 And we're looking for the click event.

126
00:06:00,540 --> 00:06:05,000
 And it says, open print, quote, click, quote, comma.

127
00:06:05,140 --> 00:06:07,840
 And then what I have is literally code.

128
00:06:07,840 --> 00:06:13,240
 And again, first class functions, the function keyword returns code

129
00:06:13,240 --> 00:06:18,400
 so that we are doing the second parameter to add event listener.

130
00:06:18,400 --> 00:06:20,480
 So we're creating a function,

131
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:23,400
 but you'll notice the function currently has no parameters,

132
00:06:23,400 --> 00:06:25,240
 and it has no name, open curly brace.

133
00:06:25,240 --> 00:06:28,140
 It's an anonymous function, and it only has one line of code,

134
00:06:28,140 --> 00:06:31,180
 document, get element, ID, fun, dot style.

135
00:06:31,180 --> 00:06:33,540
 That's how we get our hands on the CSS.

136
00:06:33,680 --> 00:06:38,800
 Display is a CSS value, and we're going to set it to the string block.

137
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:40,540
 So that is our show.

138
00:06:40,540 --> 00:06:44,100
 And we'll see that when we do the poof, the add event listener,

139
00:06:44,100 --> 00:06:46,740
 you know, on the hide button,

140
00:06:46,740 --> 00:06:48,900
 we're going to have an event listener for clicking.

141
00:06:48,900 --> 00:06:51,840
 And in this one, we're going to set the display none,

142
00:06:51,840 --> 00:06:54,300
 which means it's going to hide, so you click on hide.

143
00:06:54,300 --> 00:06:56,780
 But you'll see a slightly different syntax,

144
00:06:56,780 --> 00:06:58,300
 and you'll see the syntax a lot

145
00:06:58,300 --> 00:07:02,980
 because that early JavaScript, there was only one syntax for this,

146
00:07:03,100 --> 00:07:05,600
 and now there's sort of more clever syntaxes

147
00:07:05,600 --> 00:07:07,340
 in later versions of JavaScript.

148
00:07:07,340 --> 00:07:13,480
 And a key thing to remember is that this second example for the poof,

149
00:07:13,480 --> 00:07:18,200
 open parent element equals greater than,

150
00:07:18,200 --> 00:07:22,140
 which is kind of like a right arrow, equals document, get element, ID, fun.

151
00:07:22,140 --> 00:07:25,880
 This is a shortcut to define a function,

152
00:07:25,880 --> 00:07:27,540
 to define a function with no name.

153
00:07:27,540 --> 00:07:29,980
 And so for all intents and purposes,

154
00:07:30,100 --> 00:07:32,940
 these two bits of code are equivalent.

155
00:07:32,940 --> 00:07:38,800
 We're saying when there is a click on the poof item,

156
00:07:38,800 --> 00:07:42,480
 we're going to call this function that has no name,

157
00:07:42,480 --> 00:07:44,280
 but it takes as one parameter of the event.

158
00:07:44,280 --> 00:07:46,700
 The event is a parameter to all these little events

159
00:07:46,700 --> 00:07:50,480
 that the browser sets up when it calls us.

160
00:07:50,480 --> 00:07:51,940
 And then we're not going to use it, actually.

161
00:07:51,940 --> 00:07:55,640
 We just say document, get element, ID, fun, style dot display equals none,

162
00:07:55,640 --> 00:07:58,180
 which makes it vanish. Okay?

163
00:07:59,140 --> 00:08:04,600
 So if you run this, 13-css.htm, you click on hide, the header goes away.

164
00:08:04,600 --> 00:08:07,900
 You click on show, it comes back. You click on hide, it goes away.

165
00:08:07,900 --> 00:08:13,800
 And so this is just an example of how you can modify CSS.

